  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Helps track potential money laundering activities\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established penalties for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering\n- Expanded reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Strengthened anti-money laundering provisions\n- Enhanced information sharing between law enforcement agencies\n- Increased compliance requirements for financial institutions\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Updated and modernized existing money laundering regulations\n- Expanded enforcement capabilities\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define various money laundering offenses and establish criminal penalties.\n\nThese statutes work together to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities in the United States.",
